#: ../../../topics/practices.rst:83
msgid "Distributed crawls"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/practices.rst:85
msgid ""
"Scrapy doesn't provide any built-in facility for running crawls in a "
"distribute (multi-server) manner. However, there are some ways to distribute "
"crawls, which vary depending on how you plan to distribute them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/practices.rst:89
msgid ""
"If you have many spiders, the obvious way to distribute the load is to setup "
"many Scrapyd instances and distribute spider runs among those."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/practices.rst:92
msgid ""
"If you instead want to run a single (big) spider through many machines, what "
"you usually do is partition the urls to crawl and send them to each separate "
"spider. Here is a concrete example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/practices.rst:96
msgid ""
"First, you prepare the list of urls to crawl and put them into separate "
"files/urls::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/practices.rst:99
msgid ""
"http://somedomain.com/urls-to-crawl/spider1/part1.list\n"
"http://somedomain.com/urls-to-crawl/spider1/part2.list\n"
"http://somedomain.com/urls-to-crawl/spider1/part3.list"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/practices.rst:103
msgid ""
"Then you fire a spider run on 3 different Scrapyd servers. The spider would "
"receive a (spider) argument ``part`` with the number of the partition to "
"crawl::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/practices.rst:107
msgid ""
"curl http://scrapy1.mycompany.com:6800/schedule.json -d project=myproject -d "
"spider=spider1 -d part=1\n"
"curl http://scrapy2.mycompany.com:6800/schedule.json -d project=myproject -d "
"spider=spider1 -d part=2\n"
"curl http://scrapy3.mycompany.com:6800/schedule.json -d project=myproject -d "
"spider=spider1 -d part=3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/practices.rst:114
msgid "Avoiding getting banned"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/practices.rst:116
msgid ""
"Some websites implement certain measures to prevent bots from crawling them, "
"with varying degrees of sophistication. Getting around those measures can be "
"difficult and tricky, and may sometimes require special infrastructure. "
"Please consider contacting `commercial support`_ if in doubt."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/practices.rst:121
msgid ""
"Here are some tips to keep in mind when dealing with these kind of sites:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/practices.rst:123
msgid ""
"rotate your user agent from a pool of well-known ones from browsers (google "
"around to get a list of them)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/practices.rst:125
msgid ""
"disable cookies (see :setting:`COOKIES_ENABLED`) as some sites may use "
"cookies to spot bot behaviour"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/practices.rst:127
msgid ""
"use download delays (2 or higher). See :setting:`DOWNLOAD_DELAY` setting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/practices.rst:128
msgid ""
"if possible, use `Google cache`_ to fetch pages, instead of hitting the "
"sites directly"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/practices.rst:130
msgid ""
"use a pool of rotating IPs. For example, the free `Tor project`_ or paid "
"services like `ProxyMesh`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/practices.rst:132
msgid ""
"use a highly distributed downloader that circumvents bans internally, so you "
"can just focus on parsing clean pages. One example of such downloaders is "
"`Crawlera`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/practices.rst:136
msgid ""
"If you are still unable to prevent your bot getting banned, consider "
"contacting `commercial support`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/practices.rst:150
msgid "Dynamic Creation of Item Classes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/practices.rst:152
msgid ""
"For applications in which the structure of item class is to be determined by "
"user input, or other changing conditions, you can dynamically create item "
"classes instead of manually coding them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/practices.rst:159
msgid ""
"from scrapy.item import DictItem, Field\n"
"\n"
"def create_item_class(class_name, field_list):\n"
"    field_dict = {}\n"
"    for field_name in field_list:\n"
"        field_dict[field_name] = Field()\n"
"\n"
"    return type(class_name, (DictItem,), field_dict)"
msgstr ""
